lume brings two strands of research - cartography and »relational« anthropology - into a closer dialogue. It provides case studies in Africa as well as lessons to be learned from other continents (e.g. North America, Asia and Australia). The contributors create a deepened understanding of indigenous ontologies for a further decolonization of maps, and thus advance current debates in the social sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aAnthropology. 4aCritical Cartography. 4aCultural Anthropology. 4aCultural Geography. 4aCulture. 4aGeography. 4aHuman Ecology. 4aHunter-gatherers. 4aIndigenous Peoples. 4aNature. 4aRelational Ontologies. 4aSpace. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aCritical Cartography.  aCultural Anthropology.  aCultural Geography.  aCulture.  aGeography.  aHuman Ecology.  aHunter-gatherers.  aIndigenous Peoples.  aNature.  aRelational Ontologies.  aSpace.1 aBrody, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDieckmann, Ute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDieckmann, Ute, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEide, Øyvind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanuses, Welhemina Suro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Mara Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReumont, Frederik von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkaanes, Thea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSullivan, Sian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVermeylen, Saskia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWickens Pearce, Margaret, econtributo